[src:plug-elixir/elixir-programming-language] The community organizes yearly events in the United States, Europe, and Japan, as well as minor local events and conferences.
[src:plug-elixir/elixir-programming-language] José Valim created the Elixir programming language as a research and development project at Plataformatec.
[src:plug-elixir/elixir-programming-language] His goals were to enable higher extensibility and productivity in the Erlang VM while maintaining compatibility with Erlang's ecosystem.
[src:plug-elixir/elixir-programming-language] Elixir is aimed at large-scale sites and apps.
[src:plug-elixir/elixir-programming-language] It uses features of Ruby, Erlang, and Clojure to develop a high-concurrency and low-latency language.
[src:plug-elixir/elixir-programming-language] It was designed to handle large data volumes.
[src:plug-elixir/elixir-programming-language] Elixir is also used in telecommunications, e-commerce, and finance.
[src:plug-elixir/elixir-programming-language] In 2021, the Numerical Elixir effort was announced with the goal of bringing machine learning, neural networks, GPU compilation, data processing, and computational notebooks to the Elixir ecosystem.
[src:plug-elixir/elixir-programming-language] The following examples can be run in an `iex` shell or saved in a file and run from the command line by typing `elixir *<filename>*`.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The Erlang programming language has data, pattern matching, and functional programming.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The sequential subset of the Erlang language supports eager evaluation, single assignment, and dynamic typing.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] A normal Erlang application is built out of hundreds of small Erlang processes.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] It was originally proprietary software within Ericsson, developed by Joe Armstrong, Robert Virding, and Mike Williams in 1986, but was released as free and open-source software in 1998.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Erlang/OTP is supported and maintained by the Open Telecom Platform (OTP) product unit at Ericsson.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The name *Erlang*, attributed to Bjarne Däcker, has been presumed by those working on the telephony switches (for whom the language was designed) to be a reference to Danish mathematician and engineer Agner Krarup Erlang and a syllabic abbreviation of "Ericsson Language".
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Erlang was designed with the aim of improving the development of telephony applications.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The initial version of Erlang was implemented in Prolog and was influenced by the programming language PLEX used in earlier Ericsson exchanges.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] By 1988 Erlang had proven that it was suitable for prototyping telephone exchanges, but the Prolog interpreter was far too slow.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] One group within Ericsson estimated that it would need to be 40 times faster to be suitable for production use.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] In 1992, work began on the BEAM virtual machine (VM), which compiles Erlang to C using a mix of natively compiled code and threaded code to strike a balance between performance and disk space.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] According to co-inventor Joe Armstrong, the language went from laboratory product to real applications following the collapse of the next-generation AXE telephone exchange named *AXE-N* in 1995.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] As a result, Erlang was chosen for the next Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) exchange *AXD*.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] In February 1998, Ericsson Radio Systems banned the in-house use of Erlang for new products, citing a preference for non-proprietary languages.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The ban caused Armstrong and others to make plans to leave Ericsson.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] In March 1998 Ericsson announced the AXD301 switch, containing over a million lines of Erlang and reported to achieve a high availability of nine "9"s.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] In December 1998, the implementation of Erlang was open-sourced and most of the Erlang team resigned to form a new company, Bluetail AB.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Ericsson eventually relaxed the ban and re-hired Armstrong in 2004.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] In 2006, native symmetric multiprocessing support was added to the runtime system and VM.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Erlang applications are built of very lightweight Erlang processes in the Erlang runtime system.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The Erlang runtime system provides strict process isolation between Erlang processes (this includes data and garbage collection, separated individually by each Erlang process) and transparent communication between processes (see Location transparency) on different Erlang nodes (on different hosts).
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] In 2014, Ericsson reported Erlang was being used in its support nodes, and in GPRS, 3G and LTE mobile networks worldwide and also by Nortel and Deutsche Telekom.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Erlang is the programming language used to code WhatsApp.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] It is also the language of choice for Ejabberd – an XMPP messaging server.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Elixir is a programming language that compiles into BEAM byte code (via Erlang Abstract Format).
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Since being released as open source, Erlang has been spreading beyond telecoms, establishing itself in other vertical markets such as FinTech, gaming, healthcare, automotive, Internet of Things and blockchain.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Apart from WhatsApp, there are other companies listed as Erlang's success stories, including Vocalink (a MasterCard company), Goldman Sachs, Nintendo, AdRoll, Grindr, BT Mobile, Samsung, OpenX, and SITA.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Omitting the comments gives a much shorter program.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The above example recursively invokes the function `qsort` until nothing remains to be sorted.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The expression `[Front || Front <- Rest, Front < Pivot]` is a list comprehension, meaning "Construct a list of elements `Front` such that `Front` is a member of `Rest`, and `Front` is less than `Pivot`." `++` is the list concatenation operator.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] A comparison function can be used for more complicated structures for the sake of readability.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] A `Pivot` is taken from the first parameter given to `qsort()` and the rest of `Lists` is named `Rest`.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The anonymous function is named `Smaller` in the parameter list of the second definition of `qsort` so that it can be referenced by that name within that function.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] It is not named in the first definition of `qsort`, which deals with the base case of an empty list and thus has no need of this function, let alone a name for it.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Integers are written as sequences of decimal digits, for example, 12, 12375 and -23427 are integers.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Integer arithmetic is exact and only limited by available memory on the machine.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Atoms are used within a program to denote distinguished values.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] They are written as strings of consecutive alphanumeric characters, the first character being lowercase.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Atoms can contain any character if they are enclosed within single quotes and an escape convention exists which allows any character to be used within an atom.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Atoms are never garbage collected and should be used with caution, especially if using dynamic atom generation.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] References are globally unique symbols whose only property is that they can be compared for equality.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Binaries provide a space-efficient way of storing binary data.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Erlang primitives exist for composing and decomposing binaries and for efficient input/output of binaries.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Pids are references to Erlang processes.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Ports are used to communicate with the external world.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Tuples are containers for a fixed number of Erlang data types.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The arguments can be primitive data types or compound data types.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Any element of a tuple can be accessed in constant time.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Lists are containers for a variable number of Erlang data types.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The first element of a list can be accessed in constant time.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Maps contain a variable number of key-value associations.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Strings are written as doubly quoted lists of characters.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] code points for the characters in the string.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Records provide a convenient way for associating a tag with each of the elements in a tuple.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] This allows one to refer to an element of a tuple by name and not by position.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] A pre-compiler takes the record definition and replaces it with the appropriate tuple reference.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Erlang is designed with a mechanism that makes it easy for external processes to monitor for crashes (or hardware failures), rather than an in-process mechanism like exception handling used in many other programming languages.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Crashes are reported like other messages, which is the only way processes can communicate with each other, and subprocesses can be spawned cheaply (see below).
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The "let it crash" philosophy prefers that a process be completely restarted rather than trying to recover from a serious failure.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Though it still requires handling of errors, this philosophy results in less code devoted to defensive programming where error-handling code is highly contextual and specific.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] A typical Erlang application is written in the form of a supervisor tree.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] This architecture is based on a hierarchy of processes in which the top level process is known as a "supervisor".
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The supervisor then spawns multiple child processes that act either as workers or more, lower level supervisors.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Such hierarchies can exist to arbitrary depths and have proven to provide a highly scalable and fault-tolerant environment within which application functionality can be implemented.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Within a supervisor tree, all supervisor processes are responsible for managing the lifecycle of their child processes, and this includes handling situations in which those child processes crash.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Any process can become a supervisor by first spawning a child process, then calling `erlang:monitor/2` on that process.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] If the monitored process then crashes, the supervisor will receive a message containing a tuple whose first member is the atom `'DOWN'`.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The supervisor is responsible firstly for listening for such messages and for taking the appropriate action to correct the error condition.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Erlang's main strength is support for concurrency.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] It has a small but powerful set of primitives to create processes and communicate among them.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Erlang is conceptually similar to the language occam, though it recasts the ideas of communicating sequential processes (CSP) in a functional framework and uses asynchronous message passing.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Processes are the primary means to structure an Erlang application.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] They are neither operating system processes nor threads, but lightweight processes that are scheduled by BEAM.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Like operating system processes (but unlike operating system threads), they share no state with each other.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The estimated minimal overhead for each is 300 words.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Thus, many processes can be created without degrading performance.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] In 2005, a benchmark with 20 million processes was successfully performed with 64-bit Erlang on a machine with 16 GB random-access memory (RAM; total 800 bytes/process).
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Erlang has supported symmetric multiprocessing since release R11B of May 2006.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] While threads need external library support in most languages, Erlang provides language-level features to create and manage processes with the goal of simplifying concurrent programming.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Though all concurrency is explicit in Erlang, processes communicate using message passing instead of shared variables, which removes the need for explicit locks (a locking scheme is still used internally by the VM).
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Inter-process communication works via a shared-nothing asynchronous message passing system: every process has a "mailbox", a queue of messages that have been sent by other processes and not yet consumed.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] A process uses the `receive` primitive to retrieve messages that match desired patterns.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] A message-handling routine tests messages in turn against each pattern, until one of them matches.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] When the message is consumed and removed from the mailbox the process resumes execution.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] A message may comprise any Erlang structure, including primitives (integers, floats, characters, atoms), tuples, lists, and functions.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] As the example shows, processes may be created on remote nodes, and communication with them is transparent in the sense that communication with remote processes works exactly as communication with local processes.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Concurrency supports the primary method of error-handling in Erlang.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] When a process crashes, it neatly exits and sends a message to the controlling process which can then take action, such as starting a new process that takes over the old process's task.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The official reference implementation of Erlang uses BEAM.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] BEAM is included in the official distribution of Erlang, called Erlang/OTP.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] BEAM executes bytecode which is converted to threaded code at load time.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] It also includes a native code compiler on most platforms, developed by the High Performance Erlang Project (HiPE) at Uppsala University.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Since October 2001 the HiPE system is fully integrated in Ericsson's Open Source Erlang/OTP system.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] It also supports interpreting, directly from source code via abstract syntax tree, via script as of R11B-5 release of Erlang.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Erlang supports language-level Dynamic Software Updating.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] To implement this, code is loaded and managed as "module" units; the module is a compilation unit.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The system can keep two versions of a module in memory at the same time, and processes can concurrently run code from each.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The versions are referred to as the "new" and the "old" version.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] A process will not move into the new version until it makes an external call to its module.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] For the second version, we add the possibility to reset the count to zero.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Only when receiving a message consisting of the atom `code_switch` will the loop execute an external call to codeswitch/1 (`?MODULE` is a preprocessor macro for the current module).
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] If there is a new version of the *counter* module in memory, then its codeswitch/1 function will be called.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] The practice of having a specific entry-point into a new version allows the programmer to transform state to what is needed in the newer version.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] In the example, the state is kept as an integer.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] In practice, systems are built up using design principles from the Open Telecom Platform, which leads to more code upgradable designs.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Successful hot code loading is exacting.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Code must be written with care to make use of Erlang's facilities.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] In 1998, Ericsson released Erlang as free and open-source software to ensure its independence from a single vendor and to increase awareness of the language.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Erlang, together with libraries and the real-time distributed database Mnesia, forms the OTP collection of libraries.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Ericsson and a few other companies support Erlang commercially.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Since the open source release, Erlang has been used by several firms worldwide, including Nortel and Deutsche Telekom.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Although Erlang was designed to fill a niche and has remained an obscure language for most of its existence, its popularity is growing due to demand for concurrent services.
[src:plug-elixir/erlang-programming-language] Erlang has found some use in fielding massively multiplayer online role-playing game (MMORPG) servers.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] In computer science, **function composition** is an act or mechanism to combine simple functions to build more complex ones.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Like the usual composition of functions in mathematics, the result of each function is passed as the argument of the next, and the result of the last one is the result of the whole.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Programmers frequently apply functions to results of other functions, and almost all programming languages allow it.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] In some cases, the composition of functions is interesting as a function in its own right, to be used later.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Such a function can always be defined but languages with first-class functions make it easier.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] The ability to easily compose functions encourages factoring (breaking apart) functions for maintainability and code reuse.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] More generally, big systems might be built by composing whole programs.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Narrowly speaking, function composition applies to functions that operate on a finite amount of data, each step sequentially processing it before handing it to the next.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Functions that operate on potentially infinite data (a stream or other codata) are known as filters, and are instead connected in a pipeline, which is analogous to function composition and can execute concurrently.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] For example, suppose we have two functions f and g, as in *z* = *f*(*y*) and *y* = *g*(*x*).
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Composing them means we first compute *y* = *g*(*x*), and then use y to compute *z* = *f*(*y*).
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Despite differences in length, these two implementations compute the same result.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] The second implementation requires only one line of code and is colloquially referred to as a "highly composed" form.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Readability and hence maintainability is one advantage of highly composed forms, since they require fewer lines of code, minimizing a program's "surface area".
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] DeMarco and Lister empirically verify an inverse relationship between surface area and maintainability.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] On the other hand, it may be possible to overuse highly composed forms.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] A nesting of too many functions may have the opposite effect, making the code less maintainable.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] In a stack-based language, functional composition is even more natural: it is performed by concatenation, and is usually the primary method of program design.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Which will take whatever was on the stack before, apply g, then f, and leave the result on the stack.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] See postfix composition notation for the corresponding mathematical notation.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Now suppose that the combination of calling f() on the result of g() is frequently useful, and which we want to name foo() to be used as a function in its own right.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] In most languages, we can define a new function implemented by composition.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] In languages such as C, the only way to create a new function is to define it in the program source, which means that functions can't be composed at run time.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] In functional programming languages, function composition can be naturally expressed as a higher-order function or operator.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] In other programming languages you can write your own mechanisms to perform function composition.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] using the built-in composition operator (.) which can be read as *f after g* or *g composed with f*.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] The first line describes the type of (.) - it takes a pair of functions, *f*, *g* and returns a function (the lambda expression on the second line).
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Note that Haskell doesn't require specification of the exact input and output types of f and g; the a, b, c, and x are placeholders; only the relation between *f*, *g* matters (f must accept what g returns).
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] where the parameter names are immaterial, as stated above.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Michal Ševčík credits CScalfani with a systematic exposition for function composition using additional parameters.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Variants of Lisp, especially Scheme, the interchangeability of code and data together with the treatment of functions lend themselves extremely well for a recursive definition of a variadic compositional operator.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Many dialects of APL feature built in function composition using the symbol `∘`.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] This higher-order function extends function composition to dyadic application of the left side function such that `A f∘g B` is `A f g B`.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Raku like Haskell has a built in function composition operator, the main difference is it is spelled as `∘` or `o`.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Also like Haskell you could define the operator yourself.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] In fact the following is the Raku code used to define it in the Rakudo implementation.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Nim supports uniform function call syntax, which allows for arbitrary function composition through the method syntax `.` operator.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Notions of composition, including the principle of compositionality and composability, are so ubiquitous that numerous strands of research have separately evolved.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] The following is a sampling of the kind of research in which the notion of composition is central.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Whole programs or systems can be treated as functions, which can be readily composed if their inputs and outputs are well-defined.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Pipelines allowing easy composition of filters were so successful that they became a design pattern of operating systems.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Imperative procedures with side effects violate referential transparency and therefore are not cleanly composable.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] However if one considers the "state of the world" before and after running the code as its input and output, one gets a clean function.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] Composition of such functions corresponds to running the procedures one after the other.
[src:plug-elixir/function-composition-computer-science] The monad formalism uses this idea to incorporate side effects and input/output (I/O) into functional languages.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware often enables interoperability between applications that run on different operating systems, by supplying services so the application can exchange data in a standards-based way.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware sits "in the middle" between application software that may be working on different operating systems.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] It is similar to the middle layer of a three-tier single system architecture, except that it is stretched across multiple systems or applications.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Examples include EAI software, telecommunications software, transaction monitors, and messaging-and-queueing software.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] The distinction between operating system and middleware functionality is, to some extent, arbitrary.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] While core kernel functionality can only be provided by the operating system itself, some functionality previously provided by separately sold middleware is now integrated in operating systems.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] A typical example is the TCP/IP stack for telecommunications, nowadays included virtually in every operating system.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware is defined as software that provides a link between separate software applications.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] It is sometimes referred to as plumbing because it connects two applications and passes data between them.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware allows data contained in one database to be accessed through another.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] This makes it particularly useful for enterprise application integration and data integration tasks.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] It also facilitated distributed processing, the connection of multiple applications to create a larger application, usually over a network.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] when compared to the operating system and network services.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware offers some unique technological advantages for business and industry.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] For example, traditional database systems are usually deployed in closed environments where users access the system only via a restricted network or intranet (e.g., an enterprise’s internal network).
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] With the phenomenal growth of the World Wide Web, users can access virtually any database for which they have proper access rights from anywhere in the world.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware addresses the problem of varying levels of interoperability among different database structures.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware facilitates transparent access to legacy database management systems (DBMSs) or applications via a web server without regard to database-specific characteristics.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Businesses frequently use middleware applications to link information from departmental databases, such as payroll, sales, and accounting, or databases housed in multiple geographic locations.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] In the highly competitive healthcare community, laboratories make extensive use of middleware applications for data mining, laboratory information system (LIS) backup, and to combine systems during hospital mergers.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware helps bridge the gap between separate LISs in a newly formed healthcare network following a hospital buyout.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware can help software developers avoid having to write application programming interfaces (API) for every control program, by serving as an independent programming interface for their applications.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] For Future Internet network operation through traffic monitoring in multi-domain scenarios, using mediator tools (middleware) is a powerful help since they allow operators, searchers and service providers to supervise Quality of service and analyse eventual failures in telecommunication services.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Finally, e-commerce uses middleware to assist in handling rapid and secure transactions over many different types of computer environments.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] In short, middleware has become a critical element across a broad range of industries, thanks to its ability to bring together resources across dissimilar networks or computing platforms.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] In 2004 members of the European Broadcasting Union (EBU) carried out a study of Middleware with respect to system integration in broadcast environments.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] This involved system design engineering experts from 10 major European broadcasters working over a 12-month period to understand the effect of predominantly software-based products to media production and broadcasting system design techniques.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] The resulting reports Tech 3300 and Tech 3300s were published and are freely available from the EBU web site.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Message-oriented middleware (MOM) is middleware where transactions or event notifications are delivered between disparate systems or components by way of messages, often via an enterprise messaging system.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] With MOM, messages sent to the client are collected and stored until they are acted upon, while the client continues with other processing.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] software may queue, duplicate, translate and deliver messages to disparate systems or components in a messaging system.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Intelligent Middleware (IMW) provides real-time intelligence and event management through intelligent agents.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] The IMW manages the real-time processing of high volume sensor signals and turns these signals into intelligent and actionable business information.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] The actionable information is then delivered in end-user power dashboards to individual users or is pushed to systems within or outside the enterprise.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] It is able to support various heterogeneous types of hardware and software and provides an API for interfacing with external systems.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] It should have a highly scalable, distributed architecture which embeds intelligence throughout the network to transform raw data systematically into actionable and relevant knowledge.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] It can also be packaged with tools to view and manage operations and build advanced network applications most effectively.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Content-centric middleware offers a simple *provider-consumer* abstraction through which applications can issue requests for uniquely identified content, without worrying about where or how it is obtained.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Juno is one example, which allows applications to generate content requests associated with high-level delivery requirements.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] The middleware then adapts the underlying delivery to access the content from sources that are best suited to matching the requirements.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] This is therefore similar to Publish/subscribe middleware, as well as the Content-centric networking paradigm.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware enables a client to use services running on remote systems.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware, it is possible for applications to send objects and request services in an object-oriented system.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] is middleware between applications and database servers.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] integration interface that operates between embedded applications, the embedded operating system, and external applications.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliance is a generic term referring to any form of middleware that manages policy rules.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] They can mediate between data owners or producers, data aggregators, and data users.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Among heterogeneous institutional systems or networks they may be used to enforce, reconcile, and monitor agreed information management policies and laws across systems (or between jurisdictions) with divergent information policies or needs.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliances support policy-based information management processes by enabling rules-based processing, selective disclosure, and accountability and oversight.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] IBM, Red Hat, Oracle Corporation and Microsoft are some of the vendors that provide middleware software.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Vendors such as Axway, SAP, TIBCO, Informatica, Objective Interface Systems, Pervasive, ScaleOut Software and webMethods were specifically founded to provide more niche middleware solutions.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Groups such as the Apache Software Foundation, OpenSAF, the ObjectWeb Consortium (now OW2) and OASIS' AMQP encourage the development of open source middleware.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Microsoft .NET "Framework" architecture is essentially "Middleware" with typical middleware functions distributed between the various products, with most inter-computer interaction by industry standards, open APIs or RAND software licence.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] Solace provides middleware in purpose-built hardware for implementations that may experience scale.
[src:plug-elixir/middleware-distributed-applications] StormMQ provides Message Oriented Middleware as a service.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] In other words, Plug allows you to build web applications from small pieces and run them on different web servers.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Plug is used by web frameworks such as Phoenix to manage requests, responses, and websockets.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] This documentation will show some high-level examples and introduce the Plug's main building blocks.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] In order to use Plug, you need a webserver and its bindings for Plug.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Save that snippet to a file and execute it as `elixir hello_world.exs`.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Access http://localhost:4000/ and you should be greeted!
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] In the example above, we wrote our first **module plug**, called `MyPlug`.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Module plugs must define the `init/1` function and the `call/2` function.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] `call/2` is invoked with the connection and the options returned by `init/1`.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Plug v1.14 includes a connection `upgrade` API, which means it provides WebSocket support out of the box.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Let's see an example, this time using the Bandit webserver and the `websocket_adapter` project for the WebSocket bits.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Save that snippet to a file and execute it as `elixir websockets.exs`.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Access http://localhost:4000/ and you should see messages in your browser console.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] This time, we used `Plug.Router`, which allows us to define the routes used by our web application and a series of steps/plugs, such as `plug Plug.Logger`, to be executed on every request.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Furthermore, as you can see, Plug abstracts the different webservers.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] When booting up your application, the difference is between choosing `Plug.Cowboy` or `Bandit`.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] For now, we have directly started the server in a throw-away supervisor but, for production deployments, you want to start them in application supervision tree.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] See the Supervised handlers section next.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] On a production system, you likely want to start your Plug pipeline under your application's supervision tree.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Finally create `lib/my_app/my_plug.ex` with the `MyPlug` module.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Now run `mix run --no-halt` and it will start your application with a web server running at http://localhost:4001.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] In the hello world example, we defined our first plug called `MyPlug`.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] There are two types of plugs, module plugs and function plugs.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Data can be read directly from the connection and also pattern matched on.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Manipulating the connection often happens with the use of the functions defined in the `Plug.Conn` module.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] In our example, both `put_resp_content_type/2` and `send_resp/3` are defined in `Plug.Conn`.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Finally, keep in mind that a connection is a **direct interface to the underlying web server**.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] When you call `send_resp/3` above, it will immediately send the given status and body back to the client.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] This makes features like streaming a breeze to work with.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Not only that: it contains its own plug pipeline too.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] The example above says that when the router is invoked, it will invoke the `:match` plug, represented by a local (imported) `match/2` function, and then call the `:dispatch` plug which will execute the matched code.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Plug ships with many plugs that you can add to the router plug pipeline, allowing you to plug something before a route matches or before a route is dispatched to.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Note `Plug.Router` compiles all of your routes into a single function and relies on the Erlang VM to optimize the underlying routes into a tree lookup, instead of a linear lookup that would instead match route-per-route.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] This means route lookups are extremely fast in Plug!
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] This also means that a catch all `match` block is recommended to be defined as in the example above, otherwise routing fails with a function clause error (as it would in any regular Elixir function).
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Each route needs to return the connection as per the Plug specification.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] See the `Plug.Router` docs for more information.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Plug ships with a `Plug.Test` module that makes testing your plugs easy.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] You can go into more details about each of them in our docs.
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] We welcome everyone to contribute to Plug and help us tackle existing issues!
[src:plug-elixir/plug-readme] Use the issue tracker for bug reports or feature requests.
